= Potential faculty mentors


== Gene editing

*Ben P. Kleinstiver:* develops genome editing technologies for research applications and the treatment of human diseases -- engineering genome editing enzymes, optimizing CRISPR tools, and adding new functionalities to the editor toolbox

*Jong-Min Lee:* develops allele-specific genome editing strategies to address disease-causing mutations -- specifically in the context of Huntington's and neurodegeneration broadly

\

== Other interests

*Jian Shu:* developing novel methods for engineering cell fates via cell/gene engineering, single-cell omics, and advanced imaging -- alumnus of the labs of Eric Lander and Rudolf Jaenisch 

*Florian Eichler:* advancing new gene therapy trials for rare and neurological diseases, including _ex vivo_ lentiviral and _in vivo_ AAV-based approaches as trials of antisense oligonucleotides

*Ricardo Mouro Pinto:* investigating the mechanisms of mismatch repair and other processes in Huntington's disease -- including via _in vivo_ gene editing with CRISPR-Cas9

*Rudolph Tanzi:* developing 3D organoid models of Alzheimer's disease and new therapies targeting $beta$-amyloid production and amyloidosis 

*Calum Macrae:* cardiologist focused on arrhythmia susceptibility, but has relevant expertise in obtaining patents (he has five) and starting companies that straddle academia and industry -- also, I know him personally

*Anna Greka*: investigating the mechanisms of protein trafficking and degradation in proteinopathies, lipotoxicity, and developing new bioinformatic tools to investigate cellular mechanisms -- very cool work

\

== Lysosomal biology

*Susan L. Cotman:* understanding the role of endo-lysosomal function in the childhood neurodegenerative disease NCL (Batten disease) -- candidate analysis with academic and industry partners

*Raghu R. Chivukula:* identifying and mechanistically dissecting genetic disorders affecting lysosomal biology in pulmonary disease

